Subject: [PATCH] libsysbase: add getentropy() stub and wire it into the archive

Patch 0001 turns on `syscall_dir=syscalls` for `*-ps3-*`, which pulls
newlib's POSIX connectors (sysread.c, syswrite.c, etc.) into libc.a.
That solves `undefined reference to read / write` from both libsysbase's
abort.c and libstdc++'s <random>.

It does NOT solve `getentropy`, because newlib's sysgetentropy.c looks
like this:

    int getentropy(void *buf, size_t buflen) {
        return _getentropy_r(_REENT, buf, buflen);
    }

and with -DREENTRANT_SYSCALLS_PROVIDED set at newlib build time,
<reent.h> defines `_getentropy_r` as a macro that expands back into
`getentropy(buf, buflen)` — infinite self-recursion at runtime.  There
is no `-DHAVE_GETENTROPY` / opt-out knob in newlib for this; the
intended escape hatch is that the target provides its own `getentropy`
earlier in the link line.  The GCC spec (cell64lv2.h) already does that:

    --start-group -lsysbase -lc -lrt -llv2 --end-group

so a libsysbase-local definition of `getentropy` wins the group-resolve
against newlib's broken sysgetentropy.c.

For now, return -1/ENOSYS.  Callers we know about —
  * libstdc++ random_device (falls back to /dev/urandom then software PRNG)
  * newlib arc4random (calls `_getentropy_fail` -> abort, but at least
    there's no stack-smash before that)
  * libssp stack_protector (falls back to the "terminator canary")
— all handle the failure gracefully.

Phase 3 followup: replace this stub with a real implementation backed by
lv2 `sys_ss_random_number_generator` (NID 0xEBA9F175) once the sys_ss
syscall stub lands.  The file path stays; only the function body changes.

diff --git a/libgloss/libsysbase/Makefile.in b/libgloss/libsysbase/Makefile.in
--- a/libgloss/libsysbase/Makefile.in
+++ b/libgloss/libsysbase/Makefile.in
@@ -70,7 +70,7 @@ OBJS = abort.o close.o environ.o sbrk.o syscalls.o _exit.o fstat.o isatty.o \
 	   wait.o unlink.o execve.o kill.o gettod.o fork.o chmod.o sleep.o dup.o glob.o \
 	   getrusage.o globfree.o closedir.o fstat64.o link.o lseek64.o opendir.o readdir.o \
 	   readdir_r.o rmdir.o rewinddir.o rename.o seekdir.o settod.o stat.o stat64.o telldir.o \
-	   truncate.o mkdir.o umask.o utime.o times.o access.o
+	   truncate.o mkdir.o umask.o utime.o times.o access.o getentropy.o

 # Object files specific to particular targets.
 EVALOBJS = ${OBJS}
diff --git a/libgloss/libsysbase/getentropy.c b/libgloss/libsysbase/getentropy.c
new file mode 100644
--- /dev/null
+++ b/libgloss/libsysbase/getentropy.c
@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@
+#include <errno.h>
+#include <stddef.h>
+#include <unistd.h>
+
+/*
+ * Stub for getentropy(3).  Returns -1 with errno = ENOSYS so callers
+ * (libstdc++'s random_device, newlib's arc4random, libc's stack_protector)
+ * take their fallback path instead of infinite-recursing through newlib's
+ * libc/syscalls/sysgetentropy.c, which -DREENTRANT_SYSCALLS_PROVIDED turns
+ * into `getentropy -> _getentropy_r(...) -> getentropy -> ...`.
+ *
+ * A real implementation backed by PS3 lv2's sys_ss_random_number_generator
+ * (NID 0xEBA9F175) is Phase 3 / libsysutil work, not a newlib hook.  When
+ * that lands, this stub is replaced in-place, not dropped — it still has to
+ * be linked ahead of newlib/libc/syscalls/sysgetentropy.c so the toolchain
+ * spec's `--start-group -lsysbase -lc ...` group picks the libsysbase copy.
+ */
+int
+getentropy(void *buf, size_t buflen)
+{
+	(void)buf;
+	(void)buflen;
+	errno = ENOSYS;
+	return -1;
+}
